Part I - Data Exploration for PISA 2012 dataset¶

by Anh Nguyen¶

Introduction¶

The Program for International Student Assessment (PISA) is the global survey developed by the Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) to assess the competencies of 15-year-old students in reading, mathematics and science, as well as to understand their family backgrounds and educational systems. Around 510,000 students in 65 countries and economies participated in PISA 2012. Of those countries and economies, 44 took part in an assessment of creative problem-solving and 18 were evaluated in financial literacy.

Dataset structure¶

The pisa2012.csv file has 485,490 student records grouped in 636 columns.

The dataset contains the results from exams in mathematics, science, reading, financial literacy as well as students' demographic, family backgrounds, study and out-of-school time, learning methods, school and home ICT facilities, language spoken at home, students' interests and moviations, and more.

Main features of interest¶

The main features of this dataset are plausible values for mathematics, science and reading along with 3 learning time columns. According to the PISA 2012 Technical Report (LINK), these plausible values are not real test scores but random numbers drawn from the distribution of scores that could reasonably assigned to each individual. Various factors can affect these test scores, so it's best to take the average across each subgroup.

Features in the dataset that can support my investigation¶

In this project, I want to know if any factors can influence the academic performance of students and their study time. Due to the complexity of the dataset, I only keep some features of interest as below to investigate:

  • Country of residence
  • OECD membership
  • Student's gender
  • Parents' education level
  • 3 values for learning time (minutes per week) in each subject category
  • 5 plausible values in each subject category

Data Cleaning¶

There are a few things we need to do here:

  1. Replace Florida (USA), Massachusetts (USA) and Connecticut (USA) by United States
  2. Add 3 columns that take the average of 5 plausible values for each subject category
  3. Add a total score column, then remove those 15 plausible score columns
  4. Rename all columns
  5. Add a total learning time column
  6. For parents' education columns, replaced values by more descriptive names, then convert them to categorical data type

#6. For parents' education columns, replace values by more descriptive names, then convert them to categorical data type¶

According to OECD website (LINK), values in the educational level columns can be categorized as below:

  • None
  • ISCED 1: primary education
  • ISCED 2: lower secondary
  • ISCED 3B, C: vocational/pre-vocational upper secondary
  • ISCED 3A, ISCED 4: general upper secondary/non-tertiary post-secondary
  • ISCED 5B: vocational tertiary
  • ISCED 5A, 6: theoretically oriented tertiary and post-graduate
In [20]:
# Create a dictionary to map
ed_level = {
    'None'   : 'No Education',
    'ISCED 1': 'Primary Education',
    'ISCED 2': 'Lower Secondary',
    'ISCED 3B, C': 'Upper Secondary',
    'ISCED 3A, ISCED 4': 'Post Secondary',
    'ISCED 5B': 'Vocational Tertiary',
    'ISCED 5A, 6': 'Post Graduate'
}

# Replace values in 2 educational columns by mapping values in ed_level
df_copy['father_education'].replace(ed_level, inplace=True) 
df_copy['mother_education'].replace(ed_level, inplace=True)

Univariate Exploration¶

Question 1: What is the percentage of students by country?¶

In [26]:
# Set plot dimensions
plt.figure(figsize = [12, 15])

# Set base color
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]

# Define proportion
country_counts = df_copy['country'].value_counts()
country_order = country_counts.index
n_students = country_counts.sum()

# Plot
sb.countplot(data = df_copy, y = 'country', color = base_color, order = country_order)
plt.title('The percentage of students by Country')
plt.xlabel('Number of students');

# Add percentage text to each bar
for i in range (country_counts.shape[0]):
    count = country_counts[i]
    # Convert count into a percentage, and then into string
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_students)
    # Print the string value on the bar. 
    plt.text(count+1, i, pct_string, va='center')

Observation for Question 1¶

The number of students in each country is not equally represented. The first 10 countries and the last 3 countries move away from 5000 students (1%). 3 countries have highest number of students are Mexico, Italy and Spain. Liechtenstein has the lowest number of participants.

Question 4: Do scores follow a normal distribution?¶

In [29]:
# Create a function to plot histograms
def histogram (col, binsize, xlabel=None):
    bins = np.arange(0, df_copy[col].max()+binsize, binsize)
    plt.hist(data = df_copy, x = col, bins = bins)
    plt.title('{}'.format(col.replace('_', ' ').title()))
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel('Student Count')
    plt.axvline(x = df_copy[col].median(), color = 'red')
In [30]:
# Set the plot dimensions
plt.figure(figsize = [14, 10])

# Create a dictionary to map positions with columns
scores_dict = {1:'math_score', 2:'science_score', 3:'reading_score', 4:'total_score'}

# Plot
for pos, col in scores_dict.items():
    plt.subplot(2, 2, pos)
    if pos == 4:
        histogram(col, binsize = 60, xlabel = 'Score')
    else:
        histogram(col, binsize = 30, xlabel = 'Score')

Observation for Question 4¶

All score distributions are normal. 3 subject distributions have a peak at about 500.

Question 9: How does the performance in each subject by country look like?¶

In [36]:
def rank_means(col):
    # Set figure dimensions
    plt.figure(figsize = [14, 15])
    
    # Calculate mean of total score by country
    mean_vars = df_copy.groupby('country')[col].mean().sort_values(ascending=False)
    
    # Plot
    sb.barplot(data=df_copy, x=col, y='country', color=base_color, order=mean_vars.index, errorbar=None)
    plt.title('{} by Country'.format(col.replace('_', ' ').title()))
    plt.xlabel('Mean of {}'.format(col.replace('_', ' ')))
    
    # Add labels
    for i in range (mean_vars.shape[0]):
        count = mean_vars[i]
        # Convert count into string
        count_str = '{:.1f}'.format(count)
        # Print the string value on the bar 
        plt.text(count+1, i, count_str, va='center')

In this part, I want to discover which factors may affect student's performance and their study time.

When splitting genders into OECD and non-OECD countries, I noticed that gender distribution in OECD countries is equally distributed, whereas the proportion of female participants in non-OECD countries is slightly higher (51,22%). While females have better performance in Reading, males perform slightly better in Math. Both genders have similar performance in Science.

As expected, OECD countries have better performance in all Math, Science and Reading than non-OECD countries. I wonder if there is any difference if we continue breaking it to each gender, so I will explore that in the multivariate part.

To rank the mean of total score and each subject's score, I created a function called rank_means. Overall, China-Shanghai has the best performance while Peru has the worst performance. Top 10 highest scores in 3 subjects are mostly from Asia, though their ranks are slightly different from Math, Science to Reading. 3 non-Asian countries on top 10 are Liechtenstein, Estonia and Poland. Interestingly, the number of Liechtenstein students only account for 0.1% of our dataset, which is the lowest (Question 1).

I wonder if longer learning time may result in higher performance, so I created a correlation heatmap of among all learning time and score variables. I found out longer learning time doesn't lead to higher performance, but at the same time, I noticed that scores seem to correlate to each other because of high correlation coefficients. This was then confirmed using the scatter plot in Question 11, which means if a student performs well in either of Math, Science or Reading, he or she also performs well in the other two. But in general, Math and Science has the strongest correlation.

Using a heatmap to plot the group count of mother and father education level, I noticed that parents tend to have same educational levels. This is also reflected in two box plots of question 13 when I saw a similar trend between both parents with their children's total score. Students whose parents have higher level of education are more likely to perform better. Neverthesless, for parents with educational levels from Upper Secondary to Vocational Tertiary, the difference in their children's performance is less significant.

There is no significant difference in learning time between female and male students, and the same goes for those coming from OECD or non-OECD countries.

In this part, I only used 2 box plots to deep dive into the relationship between student performance or learning time with gender and OECD membership.

For student performance, when spliting out gender into OECD membership, I found out the fact that OECD students tend to perform better is still right. However, when looking specifically to the Science subject, the median score of females is higher in OECD countries but lower in non-OECD countries.

For the learning time, while females and males have the same learning time in non-OECD countries, males have longer learning time than females in OECD countries. Interestingly, the learning time of female students in non-OECD countries is slightly longer than those from OECD countries.

Conclusions¶

This project aims to explore whether certain background factors can affect students' academic performance and how much time they spend learning.

With a large and complex dataset like PISA 2012, I only focused on some features of interest including country of residence, OECD membership, student's gender, parents' education level; as well as 15 plausible values for Math, Science, Reading along with three corresponding columns for learning time. According to the PISA 2012 Technical Report, plausible values are not real test scores but estimated numbers drawn from the similar distributions that could represent the individual tests. Since various factors can influence these scores, it's best to take the average for each subgroup.

The Univariate Exploration lets me analyze each variable on its own and understand how the data are distributed. I noticed that all scores follow a normal distribution, while learning time's distributions are skewed to the right. The distribution of genders is roughly equal, and most parents in the dataset have post-secondary or post-graduate education. Regarding countries, while most of them account for 1% of the dataset, some have significantly larger representation (like Mexico, at 7%) or smaller representation (like Liechtenstein, at 0.1%).

In the Bivariate Exploration, I explore the relationship between each independent variable and scores or learning time. Certain variables do have an impact on scores, such as OECD membership, country of residence, gender, and parents' education level. I also discovered that longer learning time doesn't necessarily lead to better performance. Notably, scores are correlated with each other, and parents often have the same educational level.

Finally, I utilized two box plots to delve deeper into the relationship between student performance or learning time with gender and OECD membership. For academic performance, students from OECD countries tend to outperform those from non-OECD countries. But for Science score, female scores in OECD countries are higher, while in non-OECD countries, female scores are lower. For learning time, in non-OECD countries, both females and males study the same amount of time. But in OECD countries, males has longer study time per week than females. Also, it's interesting that female students in non-OECD countries study a bit longer than those in OECD countries.
